text:
 Get an 18% gray card. You can get one at a photography store or you can create one on your computer. Even if your printer isn't calibrated just right, your results will still be better than without using a gray card. You can make one by:
Open up your graphic software and creating an image. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c3\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c3\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Fill the image with black. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e3\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/e3\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Reduce the opacity by 50%. This will give you that 18% gray. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f7\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/f\/f7\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Print it out. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/17\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet4.jpg\/v4-460px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/17\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet4.jpg\/v4-760px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Before taking photographs, take a shot of the gray card in the light conditions that you will be photographing in. If taking portraits, have your subject hold the gray card by their face (assuming you will be photographing their face). {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/b2\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-2Bullet1-Version-2.jpg\/v4-460px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-2Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/b2\/Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-2Bullet1-Version-2.jpg\/v4-760px-Use-an-18%25-Gray-Card-Step-2Bullet1-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"} While processing the photos, go to the gray card photo first. Set your software to adjust exposure according to that gray card image. Use those adjustments on all of the photographs taken in that session.  Remember to re-photograph the gray card if the lighting or location changes.
